File: /home/baron/projects/campfire/cmd/cf/cmd/read.go, runNATPoll (line 408-414)

In one-shot (non-follow) mode, the error retry logic is:
  if !cfg.follow {
      if peerIdx == 0 {
          return fmt.Errorf("polling peers: %w", err)
      }
  }

peerIdx is incremented modulo len(peers) BEFORE this check. So after a failure on peer 0, peerIdx becomes 1. The code continues to peer 1. If peer 1 also fails, peerIdx becomes 2 (or wraps to 0 if len=2). If it wraps to 0, the error is returned.

Problem: for a single-peer scenario (len(peers) == 1), peerIdx = (0+1) % 1 = 0. So after the FIRST failure on the only peer, peerIdx == 0 and the error is returned. This is correct.

For a 2-peer scenario where both peers fail: peer 0 fails, peerIdx becomes 1. Then the loop continues (no error returned since peerIdx != 0). Peer 1 fails, peerIdx becomes 0. Error returned. But the last error returned is from peer 1, not peer 0. This loses peer 0s error message. Minor issue.

More seriously: for 3+ peers where ONLY peer 0 fails and the others succeed, the code would return the peer 0 error after wrapping around even though a successful peer existed. Wait, no — on success the break exits the loop. The issue only manifests when ALL peers fail and peerIdx wraps.

Actually a subtle bug: if peer 0 fails then peer 1 succeeds (returns data), the cursor advances and the function breaks. Good. But if peer 0 succeeds with no messages (len(msgs) == 0), the code hits "if !cfg.follow { break }" and exits. This is the intended behavior.

The real bug: if the first poll succeeds but returns 0 messages, the cursor is NOT updated (newCursor is only set when len(msgs) > 0). But on 204 from the server, Poll returns (nil, cursor, nil) — cursor unchanged. So the next call would re-poll from the same position. This is correct for one-shot mode (no retransmission), but the cursor variable remains at the initial value regardless of server-side 204. This is intentional but worth noting the cursor never advances on empty poll.

Close reason: Fixed: one-shot NAT poll now tracks firstErr and reports it instead of the last error when all peers fail

