In cmd/cf-mcp/main.go, the non-HTTP path of handleAwait (around line 1119-1136) uses:
  for {
    select {
    case <-deadline:
      ...
    case <-time.After(interval):
    }
    ...
  }

time.After creates a new *time.Timer on every iteration. The channel is never explicitly stopped, so the timer's goroutine leaks until the GC collects it. For a 10-minute await at 2s intervals that's ~300 leaked timers.

Fix: replace with time.NewTicker outside the loop:
  ticker := time.NewTicker(interval)
  defer ticker.Stop()
  for {
    select {
    case <-deadline:
      return errResponse(...)
    case <-ticker.C:
    }
    // ... sync and check ...
  }

The deadline arm (time.After before the loop) is correct — single timer, not in a loop.

Done condition: no time.After inside a for-select in handleAwait.

Close reason: Replaced time.After(interval) inside for-select with time.NewTicker outside the loop + defer ticker.Stop(). No more per-iteration timer leaks. Build and tests pass.

## Bug

runViewRead (cmd/cf/cmd/view.go:234) fetches ALL messages with `s.ListMessages(campfireID, 0)` (no filter), then applies the predicate. This means campfire:view definition messages are included in the candidate set.

For most predicates this is harmless (the campfire:view messages don't match `(tag "memory:standing")` etc). But for negation predicates like `(not (tag "foo"))` or `(not (tag "memory:standing"))`, the campfire:view system messages will appear in results, since they don't have those tags.

The test TestViewRead_PredicateFilters manually skips view messages in its own evaluation loop (see the isViewMsg check), but runViewRead itself does NOT skip them.

## Fix
Filter out campfire:view messages before predicate application in runViewRead. Either:
1. Add a post-filter after matching: skip records whose tags include campfire:view
2. Or pre-filter using a negative filter

Simplest fix — after building matched, filter to exclude campfire:view tag:
```go
for _, m := range allMsgs {
    ctx := buildMessageContext(m)
    // Skip system messages (view definitions etc) from results.
    isSystem := false
    for _, tag := range ctx.Tags {
        if strings.HasPrefix(tag, "campfire:") {
            isSystem = true
            break
        }
    }
    if isSystem {
        continue
    }
    if predicate.Eval(pred, ctx) {
        matched = append(matched, m)
    }
}
```

