Pattern: Reinventing stdlib / readability.

Location: pkg/campfire/campfire.go:130-150 — MembershipHash().

The sort.Slice comparator manually loops over key bytes:
  sort.Slice(keys, func(i, j int) bool {
    for k := 0; k < len(keys[i]) && k < len(keys[j]); k++ {
      if keys[i][k] != keys[j][k] { return keys[i][k] < keys[j][k] }
    }
    return len(keys[i]) < len(keys[j])
  })

This is exactly bytes.Compare(keys[i], keys[j]) < 0. The standard library function handles all edge cases (empty slices, unequal lengths) correctly.

Additionally, the function copies each key into a new slice (keys[i] = make([]byte, len(m.PublicKey)); copy(keys[i], ...)) to avoid aliasing, but the sort operates on a [][]byte where the sub-slices are already independent allocations from the Members slice. The defensive copy is unnecessary.

Why it's problematic: The hand-rolled comparator is harder to read and review. Any future reader must verify it matches bytes.Compare semantics.

Suggested direction: Replace the sort.Slice comparator with bytes.Compare. Remove the unnecessary key copy loop and replace with slices.Clone or direct index access.

Close reason: Replaced hand-rolled byte comparator in MembershipHash with bytes.Compare(keys[i], keys[j]) < 0. Removed unnecessary defensive key copy loop — sub-slices are already independent allocations. Build clean, tests pass. Commit b65cc30.

File: /home/baron/projects/campfire/pkg/threshold/threshold.go, RunDKG (line 159-246)

In the goroutine for each participant (line 206-233), the drainDKG function loops calling p.ProcessAll() and routing messages via routeDKG. If routeDKG returns an error (line 178-179, 198-201), the error is logged with continue but the message is dropped. The participant that was supposed to receive this message will never get it and will block forever on its Done() channel.

The WaitGroup wg.Wait() on line 235 will then deadlock because that goroutine never returns.

The channels are buffered (n*n*8) which is generous, but if MarshalBinary fails (extremely unlikely but possible if memory allocation fails), the message is dropped and the corresponding goroutine blocks forever.

Additionally, the drainDKG function does NOT check p.Done() inside the ProcessAll loop:
  func drainDKG(p *DKGParticipant, uid uint32) {
      for {
          select {
          case <-p.Done(): return
          default:
          }
          out := p.ProcessAll()
          if len(out) == 0 { return }
          ...
      }
  }

The Done() check is non-blocking (select with default). If Done() fires and out is non-empty in the same iteration, the function returns early leaving messages unrouted. But Done() closing means the DKG is complete, so subsequent messages would be ignored anyway.

The main risk is the deadlock scenario from dropped messages due to MarshalBinary errors.

Close reason: Fixed: RunDKG goroutines now have 30s context timeout (worktree-agent-a699bc1e)

